        Conclusion - Part I<br/><br/>"Good morning everyone." I said as I entered the conference room.  Steven and Ronald were seated at the conference table with their notepads and pens ready.<br/><br/>"What do you have for us, Chief?" Ronald asked.<br/><br/>I plugged my Powerbook into the presentation projector and brought up a prepared presentation that I had been up all night writing."Huge Kingdom has a huge flaw that has permitted several individuals to manipulate inventory items in the game.  The flaw was identified during development by QA analyst Barbie and corrected by one of your programmers, Chuck." I explained.<br/><br/>"Chief, I'm confused.  If the flaw was fixed, how was it still being exploited?" Steven asked.<br/><br/>"A strange string of events happened leading to the answer.  The flaw was fixed by Chuck and checked into the source tree.  This fix was compiled into the early beta builds of the Huge Kingdom software.  Several weeks before Huge Kingdom went gold, several programmers were terminated by MMM and one QA analyst was horizontally transferred to an administrative assistant position." I answered.<br/><br/>"That was Barbie.  We had doubts whether she was actually filing her own bug reports.  When it came down to it, she wasn't qualified for the job.  I believe that a counseling form in her file reflects that." Steven interjected.<br/><br/>"Correct.  The bugs were actually found by Chuck and given to Barbie to file.  Careful examination of CVS check-in records showed that Chuck had actually fixed the bug two days before Barbie reported the bug, withdrew the fixed code, and then checked it back in after Barbie reported the bug." I said.<br/><br/>"Why would Chuck do that?  He's one of our best programmers.  He took over a lot of programming responsibility when Duke was terminated." Ronald asked. "Chuck is a good guy." <br/><br/>"That is the one part of the investigation that took me the longest to figure out, and it's fit for a soap opera script." I replied.  "Chuck and Barbie were doing a lot more than sharing code."<br/><br/>I proceeded to the next slide in my presentation.<br/><br/>"Oh man." Steven said as he stared at the e-mail on the screen.<br/><br/>"But first, let me describe the events from last evening.<br/><br/>I took Steven and Ronald back to the previous evening after my meeting with Steven:<br/><br/>(fade out to the MMM server room)<br/><br/>  "It's freaking cold in here, man." Scrap muttered as sat down on the floor of the server room.<br/><br/>"Have some coffee." I said, handing Scrap a paper cup of coffee commandeered from the MMM coffee machine.<br/><br/>"Are you really sure about all of this?" Scrap asked, glancing at the traffic scrolling across the scraptop.<br/><br/>"We're going to find out." I replied.<br/><br/>*DING*<br/><br/>A console beep erupted from the scraptop as reverse-highlighted text appeared in a console window.<br/><br/>"Woah." Scrap said quietly.  <br/><br/>"WHAT!" I asked impatiently.  I placed my hands on both sides of the scraptop and turned it to face me. <br/><br/>"That's an interesting piece of SMTP traffic you have there, boss." Scrap said with a grin.<br/><br/>I scrolled down through the headers of the captured traffic until I could read the entire message.<br/><br/><b><br/>From: chuckie@chuckiesplace.com<br/>To: trotster@hotmail.com<br/>Subject: hey<br/><br/>Steve is on the phone with Ronald.  There's a meeting tomorrow morning.  I have tried to tell you that this wasn't worth it, but you wouldn't listen.  I should have never have let you talk me into this because it was stupid to begin with.  The holes are being closed in tonight's maintenance window.  You should have listened to me about a lot of things.  Love, C<br/></b><br/><br/>I finished my story to find Ronald and Steven mesmerized.<br/><br/>And they hadn't even heard the entire story ...
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer"></div>
